html.body: NF-B is a key transcription factor of M1 macrophages and is required for induction of a large number of inflammatory genes, including those encoding TNF-, IL-1, IL-6, IL-12p40 and cyclooxygenase-2

In the classical NF-B signaling pathway, the activated IKK complex, predominantly acting through IKK in an IKK-dependent manner, catalyzes the phosphorylation of IBs (at sites equivalent to Ser32 and Ser36 of IB), polyubiquitination (at sites equivalent to Lys21 and Lys22 of IB) and subsequent degradation by the 26S proteasome. The released NF-B dimers (in this pathway, most commonly the p50RelA dimer) translocate to the nucleus, bind DNA and activate gene transcription.
